    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Chlamys tincta, Ostrea multistriata&nbsp;</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_1035",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Shell valves equal in size and both domed, oval in outline and longer (hinge to opening) than wide. An ‘ear’ next to the hinge on the one side only. Shell valves each with about 50-70 fine, radiating and prickly ribs. Colour very variable, ranging from white to yellow, but most often orange or violet. A row of distinct simple eyes are visible along the edge of the mantle, each situated on a short sensory tentacle.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_1036",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Reaches 37 mm shell height.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_1037",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Mediterranean, Azores, Angola, Namibia and southern Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Saldanha Bay to southern Mozambique.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_1038",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Found attached by their delicate byssus to the undersides of rocks or more commonly in crevices or among larger organisms, such as the ascidian <i>Pyura stolonifera</i> or nestled in the holdfasts of kelps. Usually occur singly. The brightly-coloured marginal eyes, for which this group is well known, are thought to aid scallops to sense the presence of predators.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_1039",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>All bivalves feed by drawing water in, then filtering it thought the enlarged sieve-like gills. Food particles filtered from the water are transported by cilia to the edge of the gill and then to the mouth.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_1040",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Details unknown, but almost all bivalves are broadcast spawners.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_1041",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>This is the most common small scallop found on Western Cape shores, but several other similar species occur in the warmer waters of KwaZulu-Natal and at deeper depths (for details see reference below).</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_1042",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2016). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa. (Fourth edition) Struik Nature, Cape Town. (p. 150).<br><br>Dijkstra, HH & Kilburn, RN (2001). The family Pectinidae in South Africa and Mozambique (Mollusca: Bivalvia: Pectinoidea). <i>African Invertebrates</i>, 42, 263-321.<br><br>Kilburn, R & Rippey, E (1982). Sea Shells of Southern Africa. Macmillan South Africa, Johannesburg (p. 171, as <i>Chlamys tincta</i>).",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_1043",
